result.execSummary:
The defendant Shawn S Quinnell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Methamphetamine [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).
  • Disorderly Conduct - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Repeater, Domestic Abuse], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

records.addlTxt:
Absolute sobriety. No controlled substances without a valid prescription.
Bond is being modified so defendant can attend treatment as an ATR. When he is finished with treatment, his cash bonds will be reinstated and he will be returned to the Wood County Jail.

3:34 PM Defendant Shawn S Quinnell appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney David R. Knaapen in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Jeanne Lila Zamzow in court for Shawn S Quinnell. 
Michael Burger is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Knaapen. He is a police officer with the Wisconsin Rapids Police Department. On 5/30/22, he was dispatched to a residence in the City of Wisconsin Rapids regarding a disturbance. He spoke to two people who indicated that defendant was at the residence and defendant threw a chair and scattered cereal around the kitchen.  Defendant threatened to kill himself and cut his wrists with a scissors. They indicated that defendant had previously lived there.  They were fearful for their safety.  Other officers located defendant at Robinson Park and he was transported to the jail.  When he was booked into a jail, a bag with a white powdery substance was located in his wallet. The substance tested positive for methamphetamine.  He was advised that defendant was out on bond.  The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom.  Attorney Zamzow cross-examines witness.  
Attorney Knaapen asks Court take judicial notice of Wood County case 22CF94, a case defendant was out on bond for. Court takes judicial notice. He also asks Court take judicial notice of Wood County case 21CM336, two domestic abuse convictions. Court takes judicial notice.
Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed. Defendant stands mute and Court enters plea of not guilty to all counts.
Attorney Zamzow states that defendant's probation officer wishes to send him to an ATR treatment program and asks bond be modified to signature bond.
Attorney Knaapen states that he asks that it be modiified.
Final pre-trial scheduled for September 16, 2022 at 09:00 am.
Bail/bond hearing on June 20, 2022 at 11:15 am.
Preliminary hearing and Arraignment on June 20, 2022 at 11:15 am.
